 Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Southern French: variant of   St  .   Romain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Romain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Altagrace, Aurore, Camille, Dominique, Edele, Georges, Henri, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Jean-Michel, Jeanmarie.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and English: variant of   Roman  ."]}]},{"name":"Amand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Walloon, and in some cases possibly also English (of Norman origin), Dutch, or Flemish: from the Old French personal name <i>Amand</i>, <i>Amant</i>, Latin <i>amandus</i> ‘suitable to be loved’, the name of a 5th-century bishop of Bordeaux and several other Christian saints. In England it was also used as a female personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Ament","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Amand  .","German: variant of   Amend  .","Hungarian (<b>Áment</b>): probably of German origin (see 2 above). The surname <i>Ament</i>, presumably of Hungarian origin, is also found in Croatia."]}]},{"name":"Ida","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Norman name, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>īd</i> ‘work’. This died out during the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, influenced by its use in  Tennyson's  The Princess (  1847 ) for the central character, who devotes herself to the cause of women's rights and women's education in a thoroughly Victorian way. The name is also associated with Mount Ida in Crete, which was connected in classical times with the worship of Zeus, king of the gods, who was supposed to have been brought up in a cave on the mountainside. In the 1930s it became famous as the name of the film star  Ida Lupino  (  1914–1995 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ida de St Amand was born in 1395, in Hornchurch, Essex, England, her father, Third Baron Almaric de Saint Amand, was 54 and her mother, Alianore Lavynton, was 36. She married Thomas West 2nd Baron West before 2 July 1406, in Dartmouth, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died on 6 November 1416, in England, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1395–6 November 1416":"1395–6. november 1416","1395–1416":"1395–1416","1392–1415":"1392–1415","1406–Female":"1406–Surnud","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1341–1402":"1341–1402","1360–1426":"1360–1426","30 September 1415":"30. september 1415","2 July 1406":"2. juuli 1406","1341":"1341","1395":"1395","before 2 July 1406":"enne 2. juulit 1406","6 November 1416":"6. november 1416","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","6 May 1397":"6. mai 1397","1402":"1402","about 1415":"umbes 1415","13 June 1402":"13. juuni 1402","1406":"1406","1416":"1416","Etchingham, Sussex, England":"Etchingham, Sussex, England","England":"England","Hornchurch, Essex, England":"Hornchurch, Essex, England","Dartmouth, Devon, England":"Dartmouth, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1395–6 November 1416":"1395–6. marraskuuta 1416","1395–1416":"1395–1416","1392–1415":"1392–1415","1406–Female":"1406–Kuollut","1415–Female":"1415–Kuollut","1341–1402":"1341–1402","1360–1426":"1360–1426","30 September 1415":"30. syyskuuta 1415","2 July 1406":"2. heinäkuuta 1406","1341":"1341","1395":"1395","before 2 July 1406":"ennen